[2] UK (Mid Wales)
Date: Fri 5 Apr 2013
Source: ITV Wales [edited]
http://www.itv.com/news/wales/update/2013-04-02/powys-measles-cases-double-in-a-week/


The number of cases of measles in Powys have almost doubled in the last week to 41. The Powys Teaching Health Board says the outbreak is concentrated in the north of the county with most cases found in school age children, where the disease can spread easily, but people of all ages can be affected. In Powys 1 in 4 teenagers have not had 2 MMR (measles, mumps, and rubella) jabs and therefore are not fully protected against measles. Until now the outbreak had been focused in south west Wales.

Measles is a serious disease that can lead to long term health issues such as eye disorders, deafness , brain damage, and even death. It is very important that everyone is vaccinated against this disease. One dose of the MMR jab will protect 90 percent of children and the recommended 2 doses of MMR jab will provide 99 percent protection against measles. The MMR jab is safe and offers the only protection against measles.

--
