Africa
------
[5] Benin (Atakora)
Date: Thu 21 Mar 2013
Source: La Presse du Jour [in French, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
http://www.lapressedujour.net/?p=22893


Many cases of measles have been reported, in recent days, in the health zone of Materi-Tuieta-Cobly [Atakora department], suggesting an epidemic in the area.

A fever of 39 to 40 deg C [102.2-104 deg F], a runny nose, dry cough, conjunctivitis, lacrimation [shedding tears], edema [swelling] of the eyelids, puffy eyes, diarrhea, abdominal pain, anorexia, vomiting, are some typical signs of measles exhibited by many children in the health area of Materi-Tuieta-Cobly. The number of children with these signs (of the disease) is increasing, with the situation becoming a full-blown measles epidemic.

It should be noted that measles is a disease caused by a virus of the family _Paramyxoviridae_ and it causes respiratory disease. Measles, a highly contagious viral disease, is the most common eruptive disease accompanied by fever. Its complications can be rapidly fatal to humans.

The head doctor of this health zone, Dr Oke Raimi, is aware of this fact. He has taken immediate measures to contain the disease, including increasing the staff in some facilities to allow for the immediate care of the many cases already recorded, and those that could be coming, without delay, and assured that steps will be taken for the rapid evacuation to the zonal hospital, Saint John of God in Tanguieta, for intensive care of cases suffering complications.

[Byline: Boniface Kolawole Biaou]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Benin, formerly known as Dahomey, is one of Africa's most stable democracies. Benin is severely underdeveloped, and the economy relies heavily on trade with its eastern neighbour, Nigeria. - Mod.CP

