[6] Nigeria (Gombe)
Date: Tue 2 Apr 2013
Source: Leadership [edited]
http://leadership.ng/nga/articles/51349/2013/04/02/gombe_state_govt_records_173_cases_measles_3_months.html


The Gombe State Ministry of Health said on Tuesday [2 Apr 2013] it had recorded 173 suspected cases of measles in 4 local government areas in the last 3 months. The areas are Gombe, Balanga, Dukku, and Nafada.

The State Epidemiologist, Dr Joshua Abubakar, told the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) in Gombe that out of the cases, 10 were confirmed and currently undergoing treatment. Abubakar said the figure represented cases reported from January [2013] to date. He said when such reports were received, the ministry would immediately conduct immunisation mop-ups in the areas concerned. The epidemiologist attributed the cause to lack of adequate immunisation coverage in the areas. He, however, said that lack of political commitment and will during the immunisation campaign was a major setback. Abubakar, however, commended partners for development such as UNICEF, WHO, and the National Primary Health Care Development Agency for their contributions. He also urged them not to relent in their efforts. "If local government councils would pay their counterpart funds for immunisation frequently, I am sure there would not be a problem," he said.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Low immunization coverage still comes up as the reason for the escalating number of measles cases countrywide, calling for mop-up campaigns in the immediate term and, subsequently, a review of the country's measles control strategy to address the setbacks and reinforce strong areas of the program.

Maps of Nigeria can be seen at http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/nigeria.pdf and http://healthmap.org/r/6dG5. - Mod.JFW]

